73
00:03:02,107 --> 00:03:03,525
Hey, look at this.

74
00:03:03,609 --> 00:03:06,195
A photo from the first day
we moved into this place.

75
00:03:06,278 --> 00:03:07,988
BOTH:
Aw...

76
00:03:08,072 --> 00:03:10,115
So many great memories.

77
00:03:10,199 --> 00:03:13,118
See? That is exactly the type
of crap you should be trashing.

78
00:03:13,160 --> 00:03:16,246
So you don't keep
any photos?

79
00:03:16,288 --> 00:03:19,291
No, they're like love letters
or yearbooks or someone's ashes.

80
00:03:19,375 --> 00:03:20,918
They just take up space.

81
00:03:21,001 --> 00:03:23,796
Besides, Stella's not gonna
let you keep half of this junk.

82
00:03:23,879 --> 00:03:24,797
Why wouldn't she?

83
00:03:24,880 --> 00:03:26,632
(both chuckle)

84
00:03:26,715 --> 00:03:28,801
Oh, Ted, oh, sweetie.

85
00:03:28,842 --> 00:03:30,427
Okay, here's the thing
that guys only learn

86
00:03:30,511 --> 00:03:32,304
after they move in
with a woman.

87
00:03:32,346 --> 00:03:34,390
All of your stuff is stupid.

88
00:03:34,473 --> 00:03:35,849
Like what?

89
00:03:35,891 --> 00:03:39,561
Um, like anything you bought
at a Renaissance Faire.

90
00:03:39,645 --> 00:03:42,147
Hey, hey, there's not enough
mead in the world

91
00:03:42,189 --> 00:03:43,983
to make me get rid
of my flail.

92
00:03:44,066 --> 00:03:45,651
Oh, hey, uh, Ted,

93
00:03:45,734 --> 00:03:47,695
since we're clearly not getting
our security deposit back,

94
00:03:47,778 --> 00:03:49,989
I thought maybe you could
reimburse me for my half.

95
00:03:50,072 --> 00:03:51,031
Wait a second--
why should I

96
00:03:51,115 --> 00:03:52,491
have to pay more than you?

97
00:03:52,574 --> 00:03:54,994
Because you treated this
apartment the way John Bonham

98
00:03:55,077 --> 00:03:56,996
treated his central nervous
system.

99
00:03:57,079 --> 00:03:58,664
That's not true.

100
00:03:58,747 --> 00:04:00,708
Exhibit A.

101
00:04:02,751 --> 00:04:03,919
Hey.
Hey.

102
00:04:03,961 --> 00:04:04,920
What's that?

103
00:04:05,004 --> 00:04:08,173
A 1986 World Book
encyclopaedia.

104
00:04:08,215 --> 00:04:10,009
It's exactly the one
I grew up with.

105
00:04:10,050 --> 00:04:11,510
Encyclopaedia?

106
00:04:11,552 --> 00:04:14,555
Oh, you think it should
be pronounced encyclo-pee-dia.

107
00:04:15,556 --> 00:04:17,016
It's a common mistake.

108
00:04:17,099 --> 00:04:18,726
But if you look at that squished
together "ae" symbol

109
00:04:18,809 --> 00:04:20,561
in this here encyclopaedia,

110
00:04:20,644 --> 00:04:22,855
you'll learn that
it's a ligature derived

111
00:04:22,938 --> 00:04:25,482
from the Anglo-Saxon
rune ash...

112
00:04:29,611 --> 00:04:33,824
You know, you're gonna have
to paedia for that.

113
00:04:35,159 --> 00:04:37,286
But you never did.

114
00:04:37,369 --> 00:04:39,455
And then there's Exhibit B.

115
00:04:42,416 --> 00:04:45,419
Good morrow, fair gentles.

116
00:04:45,461 --> 00:04:47,880
Look what I won
at the Renaissance Faire.

117
00:04:47,921 --> 00:04:52,092
Ooh!

118
00:04:52,176 --> 00:04:54,678
And you're also responsible
for any damage Robin did

119
00:04:54,720 --> 00:04:55,804
when she was your girlfriend.

120
00:04:55,846 --> 00:04:57,765
Whoa. What damage did I cause?

121
00:04:57,848 --> 00:04:59,975
Do you remember that night
when you drank

122
00:05:00,017 --> 00:05:02,311
the 12'er of Molson
and you got all super Canadian?

123
00:05:05,189 --> 00:05:07,733
(Canadian accent):
Stanley Cup, game six, eh?

124
00:05:07,816 --> 00:05:09,568
The Rangers are

125
00:05:09,610 --> 00:05:12,279
about to be sorry they ever
played shinny with the Canucks.

126
00:05:12,321 --> 00:05:13,614
Hey, hey, Robin.
Yeah?

127
00:05:13,656 --> 00:05:14,740
I'll give you 20 bucks if you

128
00:05:14,823 --> 00:05:16,408
can shoot it through
this front door.

129
00:05:16,450 --> 00:05:20,245
Oh, you're nuttier than
a Tim Horton's maple log.

130
00:05:20,329 --> 00:05:22,289
Timmy Ho!

131
00:05:22,373 --> 00:05:26,919
That's it, Robin.
Give me the stick.

132
00:05:27,002 --> 00:05:28,545
I'll give you summer teeth.

133
00:05:28,629 --> 00:05:30,714
Some are here, some are there.

134
00:05:30,756 --> 00:05:33,133
Robin, give me the stick,

135
00:05:33,217 --> 00:05:34,927
Take off, hoser.

136
00:05:35,010 --> 00:05:36,011
GUYS:
Whoa!

137
00:05:36,095 --> 00:05:37,012
That's it!

138
00:05:37,096 --> 00:05:38,013
Hey, hey!

139
00:05:38,097 --> 00:05:39,014
Get her, boys, get her!

140
00:05:39,098 --> 00:05:40,015
Scrap?! I'll scrap!

141
00:05:40,099 --> 00:05:41,642
Guys, come on!
For America.

142
00:05:41,684 --> 00:05:45,437
All right, break it,
break it up!

143
00:05:45,521 --> 00:05:47,523
Ted, no!

144
00:05:47,606 --> 00:05:50,025
You never break up a girl fight!

145
00:05:50,109 --> 00:05:53,487
Never! (groans)

146
00:05:54,488 --> 00:05:56,448
Entirely Barney's fault.

147
00:05:56,490 --> 00:06:01,745
As, by the way, is the big
scorch mark over the fireplace.

148
00:06:01,787 --> 00:06:04,915
<i>NARRATOR:
Kids, to understand
the story of the scorch mark,</i>

149
00:06:04,957 --> 00:06:07,459
<i>I first need to tell you
the story of the intervention</i>

150
00:06:07,543 --> 00:06:08,544
<i>for our friend Stewart.</i>

151
00:06:08,585 --> 00:06:09,545
What's going on?

152
00:06:09,628 --> 00:06:13,507
Stewart, this is
an intervention.

153
00:06:13,549 --> 00:06:16,760
The alcohol changes
you, Stewart.

154
00:06:16,844 --> 00:06:19,263
It makes you a
different person.

155
00:06:19,346 --> 00:06:22,391
And I'm in love with
the man that I married.

156
00:06:22,474 --> 00:06:24,810
Thank you.

157
00:06:24,893 --> 00:06:28,564
(voice breaking):
This is just the push I need.

158
00:06:28,647 --> 00:06:31,066
I love you guys.

159
00:06:31,150 --> 00:06:35,821
Hey, hey!
There's the birthday boy.

160
00:06:35,904 --> 00:06:38,657
Time to let the party monster
out of its cage, Stewie!

161
00:06:38,741 --> 00:06:39,992
No!

162
00:06:40,075 --> 00:06:41,493
Come on, buddy.

163
00:06:41,577 --> 00:06:43,996
People don't want to see
Bruce Banner, dude.

164
00:06:44,079 --> 00:06:45,581
They want to see the Hulk.

165
00:06:45,622 --> 00:06:49,043
Hulk, Hulk, Hulk... What?

166
00:06:49,126 --> 00:06:52,046
Oh...

167
00:06:52,129 --> 00:06:55,633
(chuckles)

168
00:06:55,716 --> 00:06:57,968
That's what I get for skimming
the E-vite.

169
00:06:59,386 --> 00:07:02,097
<i>TED:
Later that day, we celebrated</i>

170
00:07:02,181 --> 00:07:03,390
<i>our first successful
intervention.</i>

171
00:07:03,474 --> 00:07:06,435
I am really proud of us
for helping Stewart.

172
00:07:06,518 --> 00:07:09,396
Yeah, what an amazing
honest, human moment.

173
00:07:09,480 --> 00:07:11,523
I agree. Yay us.

174
00:07:11,607 --> 00:07:14,652
Marshall, are you really gonna
keep wearing that hat?

175
00:07:14,693 --> 00:07:16,236
Yeah, it's been two weeks,
Marshall.

176
00:07:16,320 --> 00:07:18,906
Two awesome weeks...

177
00:07:18,947 --> 00:07:22,618
and heck, yeah,
I'm gonna keep wearing it.

178
00:07:27,581 --> 00:07:29,041
Hey.

179
00:07:29,124 --> 00:07:31,418
Marshall,

180
00:07:31,460 --> 00:07:33,545
this is
an intervention.

181
00:07:34,838 --> 00:07:36,465
It's about the hat.

182
00:07:36,548 --> 00:07:39,218
Huh? No...

183
00:07:39,259 --> 00:07:41,178
I have it under control, okay?

184
00:07:41,220 --> 00:07:44,014
I can take it off
whenever I want to.

185
00:07:44,056 --> 00:07:46,100
Dear Marshall,

186
00:07:46,141 --> 00:07:49,395
I do not like
that stupid hat.

187
00:07:49,478 --> 00:07:52,064
I want to beat it
with a bat.

188
00:07:52,147 --> 00:07:54,817
Or maybe stab it
with a fork.

189
00:07:54,858 --> 00:07:57,152
It makes you look
like such a dork.

190
00:07:57,236 --> 00:08:00,030
<i>TED:
After that,
interventions became</i>

191
00:08:00,114 --> 00:08:01,949
<i>a pretty regular thing
around our apartment.</i>

192
00:08:02,032 --> 00:08:03,534
Shh.

193
00:08:06,662 --> 00:08:07,746
(English accent):
Cor blimey.

194
00:08:07,788 --> 00:08:09,289
This is a nice bloody surprise.

195
00:08:09,373 --> 00:08:10,958
What's this about then?

196
00:08:11,041 --> 00:08:12,584
Lily...

197
00:08:12,668 --> 00:08:16,255
it's about the weird
fake English accent.

198
00:08:16,338 --> 00:08:18,048
Oh, bollocks.

199
00:08:20,009 --> 00:08:21,468
Oh... (clears throat)

200
00:08:23,012 --> 00:08:25,889
Spray tan?

201
00:08:27,266 --> 00:08:29,393
(sobbing):
They reel you in with a coupon,

202
00:08:29,476 --> 00:08:31,312
and then you just get hooked.

203
00:08:31,353 --> 00:08:33,981
Oh, we know, sweetie, we know.

204
00:08:34,023 --> 00:08:36,650
No, no, no, no--
this is a new sweater.

205
00:08:38,986 --> 00:08:40,321
What?

206
00:08:40,404 --> 00:08:41,697
The magic tricks.

207
00:08:41,780 --> 00:08:44,116
Specifically, those
involving fire.

208
00:08:44,199 --> 00:08:46,493
Magic tricks?

209
00:08:46,577 --> 00:08:49,246
Guys, interventions are
supposed to help people,

210
00:08:49,330 --> 00:08:52,041
not attack every little thing
you don't like about them.

211
00:08:53,792 --> 00:08:55,711
I'm sorry, but that
really steams me.

212
00:08:55,794 --> 00:08:57,546
That really burns me up!

213
00:08:59,048 --> 00:09:02,593
I mean, I am filled
with a white-hot rage!

214
00:09:02,676 --> 00:09:04,678
(growling)

215
00:09:07,931 --> 00:09:08,974
(all scream)

216
00:09:09,016 --> 00:09:10,517
Thank you.

217
00:09:11,894 --> 00:09:13,187
Oh, shoot.

218
00:09:13,270 --> 00:09:14,980
I smell hair!
I smell hair!

219
00:09:15,064 --> 00:09:16,815
<i>TED:
And that's the story
of the scorch mark.</i>

220
00:09:16,857 --> 00:09:18,150
Wait, that's weird.

221
00:09:18,192 --> 00:09:19,568
When I was going
through the closet,

222
00:09:19,652 --> 00:09:21,737
I thought I saw
the intervention banner.

223
00:09:22,738 --> 00:09:23,989
S-So?

224
00:09:24,073 --> 00:09:26,575
So, the banner burned up.
Why is there a new one?

225
00:09:28,118 --> 00:09:30,120
And there are sealed letters
here from all of you

226
00:09:30,162 --> 00:09:31,413
that say "Ted."

227
00:09:31,497 --> 00:09:33,749
Were you guys planning
an intervention for me?

228
00:09:33,791 --> 00:09:36,251
Oh, that--
that was stupid.

229
00:09:36,335 --> 00:09:38,045
Yeah, just, just forget
about that.

230
00:09:38,087 --> 00:09:39,797
Wh-What was it for?
The Crocs?

231
00:09:40,881 --> 00:09:42,841
The hair product?
Not Stella.

232
00:09:44,134 --> 00:09:46,178
Oh, my God,
this was about Stella.

233
00:09:46,220 --> 00:09:49,556
I just said "Not Stella."

234
00:09:49,640 --> 00:09:52,643
So maybe it was about
your poor listening skills, Ted.

235
00:09:52,726 --> 00:09:54,311
What?
It's out of control. See?

236
00:10:04,418 --> 00:10:05,627
Ted, we do.

237
00:10:05,711 --> 00:10:07,212
We're all really happy
for you.

238
00:10:07,296 --> 00:10:09,464
Yeah. Like I said,
it was stupid.

239
00:10:09,548 --> 00:10:11,383
Well, obviously, it wasn't,
because we agreed

240
00:10:11,466 --> 00:10:13,260
not to have any more
stupid interventions

241
00:10:13,343 --> 00:10:14,511
at our intervention
intervention.

242
00:10:15,846 --> 00:10:19,308
We're having
too many interventions.

243
00:10:19,349 --> 00:10:23,645
So, what was your big, serious
oblem with me and Stella?

244
00:10:23,729 --> 00:10:24,813
Yes!

245
00:10:24,897 --> 00:10:27,149
Yes! In everyone's face!

246
00:10:27,190 --> 00:10:28,525
You all said

247
00:10:28,609 --> 00:10:29,943
the "future Barney" thing
wouldn't work.

248
00:10:30,027 --> 00:10:31,486
<i>You told me I was crazy.</i>

249
00:10:31,570 --> 00:10:34,072
<i>My shrink told me I was crazy.</i>

250
00:10:34,114 --> 00:10:35,657
Well, who's the narcissist

251
00:10:35,741 --> 00:10:38,702
with severe attachment disorder
now, Dr. Grossbard?!

252
00:10:40,704 --> 00:10:42,623
Intervention banner?
What's that for?

253
00:10:42,706 --> 00:10:45,792
Stella.
Ah.

254
00:10:46,877 --> 00:10:49,171
"Ted, I cannot stand idly by..."

255
00:10:49,213 --> 00:10:50,714
You've just been
carrying that around?

256
00:10:50,797 --> 00:10:51,840
Please, Ted?

257
